Nothing sacred?
Now, the Trump White House is targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The surest sign of regime change is when he begins to fight the statues.
Americans understand this as well as anyone else — hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of Saddam Hussein’s statue in Baghdad’s Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump government, no doubt knew what he was doing when he carried a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a bitter dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president's proposals to drastically reduce legal migration.
To be honest, Miller didn't attempt the statue itself.
A horde of pleasure boat owners and artists portraying the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried.
But he attempted to make sense of it, especially the meaning attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta, “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.
Miller correctly stated the facts, but as he himself said, it’s not really about history.
It's about the current sound of Lazarus's startling words, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming to breathe freely, / the miserable scum of your abundant shores."
Never before have "miserable scum" been so visible on our screens.
Miller did not do literary studies - he made it clear that in America Trump is not expected of these people.
This dispute about the meaning of the statue is part of a wider political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to put her words on the base of the statue after her death - knew very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was designed to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Freedom.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Expelled.
The combination of the poem and the image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, right though to change it back.
Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist who heralded Trump’s coming, argued in 2010 that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative carrying America’s flame to a dark world: “Freedom goes forward.
It carries a torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States.”
Against Limbaugh's usual, it really got to the point here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
Lazarus's great creative achievement was to see her as she would have been seen by emaciated, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often hard voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are looking for refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue responds to them with the words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, that’s not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to illuminate the path, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their strength.
