Blocking Critics on Facebook: Don’t Run for Public Office Unless You’re Ready to Listen to Voter Criticism
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
Americans loved George Washington, but this did not prevent them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism irritated him, of course.
But he didn’t shut his mouth to his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said: “You can take away the freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter.”
I will now turn to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should have tried to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor’s subordinates called this claim null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of “well and that”.
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But it's important, too.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a Democratic-dominated state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He showed a firm hand in the management of the state and commitment to its principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as a primary way of communicating with his constituents and with jokes shows on his page his bald head after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and is conducted by administration employees with taxpayers' money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply their moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters mauling the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor who appeal to their elected leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer, Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the Post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called cheat, instead of admitting they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life stance.”
In the Facebook era, it’s easy to edit your image simply by blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is a much less dusty job than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and silenced protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in numbers.
Hohen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media platforms.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casherys of Alexandria, the chairman of the Loudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
During Washington’s era of affordable postal spending, the Internet was about as disruptive as it is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Yuricola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Portzius" wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was swamped with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn’t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means acceptance of it.
