New test results for assessing the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, show that more than 80 percent of those tested were assessed as persons over 18 years of age, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (R?ttsmedicalverket) began conducting tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make the assessment of age in the asylum process more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were rated as people 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the Forensic Medicine Agency estimated that the testee was "probably a person 18 years of age or older."
In 432 cases, the report stated that a person was “probably under 18”.
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of a person is questionable.
According to Johan Geransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with those of past months.
“We don’t see much difference with the statistics over the past months, the numbers are quite consistent,” he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, “most likely, the age of the test subject is 18 years or more.”
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper “Svenska Dagbladet” found that in 243 cases, people openly stated that he was 18 this year.
The method of conducting a medical age assessment, consisting of making an x-ray of wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and radiologists, also caused criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is endocrinologist Claude Marcus from the Karolinska Institute, part of whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I had reasons to think about it, and I don’t think we need to use the measurement methods that are used now.
Biological age is thus defined very inaccurately.
If we can’t define it with certainty, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Guranssen of the Forensic Medicine Agency spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, we can say that the risk of mistaken for an adult child is small.
The biggest risk we face is when a person is 18 soon, in which case he is about 10 percent.”
