Clubs have the right to spend large sums to acquire players, but they have to balance them with legitimate sources of income in order to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs, getting into huge debts in their quest for success, in fact, cheated and risked ruin in the event that banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, the FFP stopped focusing on clubs' debts and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used at Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with good potential, and then seriously spend money in order to improve the team and create a global brand - became a difficult plan.
During the current three-year evaluation period, which is exciting in 2018, clubs can suffer losses of 30 million euros.
And, despite Platini’s disgraceful removal from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor, Alexander Ceferin, is still determined to rein in excessive spending.
“Of course, FFP is alive and we will tighten the rules as we move forward,” Andrea Traverso, who controls FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay for the purchase of Neymar’s contract at the same time, he can distribute this amount for reporting throughout the duration of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer value can be shown in annual reports as costs of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, severe sanctions were applied to PSG, as well as to Manchester City, which belongs to Abu Dhabi.
PSG were fined 60 million euros (at that rate it is 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and was ordered to limit the composition of their team in the Champions League during the 2014-1015 season 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is tracking clubs that may try to outsmart its financial inspections by inflating their revenue at the expense of companies associated with the club's owners.
Although the Qatari company could have sponsored PSG, but if the amount of funding was considered to exceed standard market prices, UEFA would not have allowed it to be considered legal income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the amount of funding for PSG from the Qatar Tourism Authority had been inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar’s earnings in PSG could come in the form of payments from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will be an ambassador for the World Cup, and such a maneuver could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
Past sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be even more closely monitoring any attempts to circumvent the rules.
As reported on Thursday, persons familiar with the situation, UEFA did not conduct preliminary discussions with PSG about the transfer of Neymar.
They spoke with the Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss the PSG’s position.
According to the latest published reports, in 2015-1016, PSG received more than 10 million euros in profit with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects that the arrival of Neymar will be a favorable ground for sponsorship deals, the sale of paraphernalia and T-shirts with the team logo.
The club assumes that the turnover will grow by at least 30 percent due to the hiring of a new player.
Unquestionably angry that one of the best players is leaving, the Spanish league tried to prevent Neymar's transfer, saying that PSG would violate financial fair play.
“This is an obvious case of ‘financial doping’, with the club and the state,” La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, meaning that the ultimate owner of PSG is Qatar.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's doubts about the club's funding by the state.
“It’s all the consequences of equity and it’s completely changed the landscape of football over the last fifteen years,” Wenger said Thursday.
“When the club belongs to the country, everything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to comply with financial fair play, because the country can have many ways and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The order and place of taking the oath will be determined by the President
Where and how the new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law was developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the order of taking the oath in the law.
From the solemn oath will be released children under 18 years, as well as incapacitated, follows from the revised text of amendments to the bill "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available "Izvestia"), which the Committee on July 11 will consider before the second reading at its meeting.
The idea of introducing the oath of citizenship of the Russian Federation instead of formal signing of documents, President Vladimir Putin supported June 6 during a meeting with the speaker of the state Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading in the bill providing for the abolition of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part 2 of article 205.2 of the criminal code), as well as for the hijacking of an aircraft, train or water transport, but - only if this act is connected with terrorism.
According to the bill, his logic was as follows: when issuing documents for citizenship, a person signs under the promise to comply with Russian legislation - having embarked on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill was submitted to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev (“United Russia”), Gennady Zyuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (“Fair Russia”) and State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies accepted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised once again.
Now it says that the order of taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, the parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state emblem and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where it is possible to place the coat of arms of the Russian Federation is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could be the registry.
Proclaim a solemn oath wishing to obtain citizenship of the Russian Federation will be after officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after he takes the oath, it follows from the finalized text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, and not from 14.
There is a rule according to which incapacitated or disabled persons, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or personally sign the text of the oath, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to release from this procedure and “other persons”.
Also, in the updated bill, a special procedure for the admission of Ukrainian citizens who are considered native speakers of the Russian language to Russian citizens is prescribed.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the statement will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
Refusal of “foreign” citizenship, as now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is impossible “for reasons beyond the control of the person”.
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including First Vice-Speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for the decision of their fate about the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the day before the head of the Duma Committee on state construction and legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (EP).
In addition, the text appeared clarification that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have writtenly renounced “other” citizenship and handed over the previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but “for reasons beyond his control” it has not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be employed at facilities and in organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country cannot become a State Duma deputy or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
