Brothers fighting for an empire of real estate worth more than $ 500 million
The two brothers are fighting for one of Victoria's largest empires in a real estate trade worth more than $500 million - forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former director of Carlton Football Club and developer Colin de Lutis lives in the Turac Palace through three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court for the division of property and assets.
Paul wants to get out of the family business in 2014, but the Supreme Court is still dragging a fierce dispute about the terms of the divorce.
Together with his mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's list of properties includes office buildings, building plots in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller, and shopping malls in the suburbs.
Under an arrangement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million, and Paul's - 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
“The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property,” he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first hearings in the Supreme Court were held.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which, according to Paul, Colin excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some facilities.
In testimony given by Colin at the start of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
“My Italian roots make me consider the family a top priority,” he wrote.
Court costs are growing like a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer have been added to the case; both sides have attracted the most prominent lawyers, including royal lawyer Allan Myers, and the best cooks.
Mrs. De Lutys and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran milk bars and gastronomic shops, and in the early 1970s bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family-owned jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grade of school and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to transfer their possessions to their sons without conflict.
“Luigi has often told me that he doesn’t want his brothers to go to court,” she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colina says that Mark received 10 million when he went out of business, and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were “dissatisfied with the financial terms of their separation.”
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL club's board of directors and, according to a 2015 biography of Eddie McGuire, the television star's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied, with a text message stating that since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing to say."
“I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and flaunt our family’s name in court,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in testimony that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
“Our father wouldn’t want to see Paul and I argue in court,” he said, adding that he “still hopes for a resolution to the conflict.”
On Friday, that hope seemed to have dissipated.
“The judgment in our case will be delivered soon by the court,” Colin wrote.
The new chief of staff trump plans to limit the flow of information to the President.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he will be first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media, hoping to keep the chief in a calmer state.
Here's what reporter Josh Dawesy says.
At a meeting held by the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, with the administration on his first working day, he outlined a major problem in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes to solve: poor channels of information to the president.
Kelly told employees that the information should go through him — in paper form or through briefings — because the president would be better off making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is completely correct, but others have already failed, trying to pacify Trump by tracking incoming information to him.
President Trump’s relationship with television dates back decades — and now that he’s in the White House, his habit of watching television is still strong.
“When Trump, as a candidate, resented unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to demonstrate to him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be persuaded,” Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico at the time that “according to six former campaign members, in order to keep under control Trump’s habit of tweeting, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant flow of praise in the information coming to him personally.”
Okay.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter habit was ever “under control” is simply ridiculous.
Maybe those campaign members know something we don’t — for example, that if it weren’t for them, Trump’s tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets that Trump hasn’t posted.
If his employees saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has been able to always keep Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by giving Trump material — reliable or not — that validates their views.
"Politician" - just for this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly give the president dubious information.
Here is one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
Trump’s current and former employees say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened in late February, when someone slipped the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Cathy Welsh was accused of “standing behind a series of leaks” in the White House.
It does not matter that Johnson is forever banned on Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he did not present specific facts or that in the past he launched false accusations and then abandoned them.
Trump read the article and began to ask employees about Welsh.
Goldmacher adds that the then chief of staff, Reince Priebus, and the secretary of staff, Rob Porter, “tried to build a system to manage the flow of papers that Trump receives and document them.”
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly’s task very difficult.
The Tyumen Prosecutor’s Office is fighting against HIV-dissident
The prosecutor’s office challenged the decision of the Kalinin district court of Tyumen, which stopped the criminal case against a local resident, whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died due to the fact that the mother is HIV-dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor's office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished, so as not to create a precedent for other HIV-dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under Part 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died from HIV infection.
According to prosecutors, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
“The woman was not treated herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist,” the prosecutor’s office of the Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case went to the Kalinin District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that “forgive his wife, has no complaints against her, she made amends and apologized”.
The prosecutor’s office did not agree with the court’s decision and appealed, demanding to cancel the decision to dismiss the case and send it for a new consideration.
The girl died, and it is impossible to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection," the press service of the prosecutor's office said.
According to the supervisory authority, she should be punished, otherwise other HIV-dissidents will follow her example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region, about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care due to the refusal of their parents.
"And this situation has already improved - for a year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV changed their opinion - they allowed to diagnose, began to take drugs," said Elena Loseva, a spokeswoman for the AIDS Center.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
What are the risks of HIV-dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first study in Russia of the so-called movement of HIV-dissidents.
HIV-dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and see their spread as a serious threat.
