"We will only be able to assess all the allegations made now after we have collected all the information and have been able to assess the situation."
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventa vessel owned by Jugend Rettet since October.
His crew is suspected of taking migrants on board with their lifeboats, which the traffickers sent directly to them, and allowing the smugglers to leave with boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting is supposed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the materials of the prosecution, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in this zone, rather out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reasons.
The code of conduct basically assumes that Juventa-type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
