Michelle Carter's sentencing for reports that prompted Conrad Roy's suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for using text messages and phone calls to instigate the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was convicted in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at Thursday's hearing, "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large until the appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, clutching her hands and lowering her eyes.
“By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy,” the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter’s lawyer said it was a “tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that in his opinion, her "age, maturity level or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read out Roy's mother Lynn Roy's statements, which read: "Not a single day has passed that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I handle it - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.
Roy's sister Camdin Roy said she was haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
“To lose someone who has been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that provides for responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter’s message.
“You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife I don’t know, there are many ways,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad" and "You only need to turn on the ignition, and you will become free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted attention with Roy's death, and forbade her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers are divided on this.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox wrote in the Los Angeles Times, “Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not jail.”
