WASP-121b refers to the so-called "hot Jupiters" - gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the solar system, but located ten times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, a year on an exoplanet lasts only 1.3 “earth” days, and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change is threatening lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and southern France, but now there are concerns that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender began to grow worse due to dry weather and insect-borne diseases; this has caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Sches, an expert from the Provence-based agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: “Lavanda in Provence is really under threat, because in recent years this plant has felt the effects of climate change: in the spring and especially in the fall, there has been much less rain.
This affects the life span of lavender.
And there are small cicadas jumping on the leaves of insects carrying micro-bacteria; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them.”
A lot is at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is very popular in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Sches says: "Instead of very long ears with a large number of large colors, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or absent.
So we have fewer parts that contain essential oil.”
Solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding varieties more drought-resistant.
