The killing of the journalist underscores the fact that Mexico is becoming increasingly dangerous.
Employees of the weekly newspaper Riodos usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crime in Sinaloa, linked to organized crime, corrupt officials, or the ongoing war of drug traffickers.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about safety.
They were told to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children with them to an office where a grenade had already been thrown in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on the board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no proof is needed, suspicions and internal sensations will be enough.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being held by the government or the cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who make the work of covering the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence is not giving a break, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that are multiplying in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year, at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter are their publisher and inspiration, Riodos co-founder Javier Valdés Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdés wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violent crime.
His absence is felt very keenly, although his presence is everywhere - a large photograph of Valdez showing his middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the Riodos building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that depict his smile, face in glasses or his signature panama.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their general trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders each year involving drug trafficking and organized crime, journalists’ killers are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although it is now much more dangerous.
Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about security at meetings, there is little benefit, says Ibarra.
“It’s very silly to waste time in this seminar,” he says.
"Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodos office in the state capital of Culiacan.
He only managed to drive a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of his car and shot 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name - which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove away in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually quickly spread across Culiacan.
But about Valdez almost everything is silent.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the U.S. last January, Sinaloa has become one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let’s not talk about the fact that one or more people are killed on the streets of Sinaloa every day, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug kings, which are more than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that the state of “calm” is just when one of the cartels takes control of the coastal state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bochorkes, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is crushed by guilt for not being able to protect his friend.
He thinks the murder was helped by two mistakes.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the cartel’s rival factions, who is fighting Guzman’s sons.
The publication could anger the sons; people who were allegedly members of the gang bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were taken to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper was seized, which wrote about the same story.
Valdés was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be there.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroeste and in 2003, together with five colleagues, founded Riodos, selling his $50 stock.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to engage in journalism without touching on the topic of drugs,” Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper has earned a reputation as a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues have grown.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this edition they could read about what no one else dared to write.
Eight years after its founding, Riodos received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for her reporting work in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdés won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating the drug trade in Mexico, wherever it led.
He frankly admitted that he was scared.
"I want to live on," he said at the CPJ Awards.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life," he said in an October interview with Rompeviento TV.
"You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either that or you're just fooling around."
I don't want to be asked, "What were you doing when there were so many deaths... why didn't you tell me what was going on?"
Riodos employees miss Valdez, a joker who scolded like a port loader, a friend generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to moan alive.
They relied on the order they set up.
He always had to wear his hat.
He was supposed to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: Has his love for the once-established order ruined him?
His death also made them question their calculations on how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you get to know their wives, their children, their legal businesses, and their underground drug-carrying airfields.
"These things were behind the line," said Bohorkes.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and a desire for self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from anything that smells bad.
The problem, says Riodos editor Andrés Villareal, is that "the smugness can be fooled... and then what happened to Javier happens."
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa — as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states, where there is a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In a room where Riodos employees gathered for security training, it was suddenly forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days before it became known that spy programs that are sold exclusively to governments are used in Mexico to spy on journalists and public activists.
Outside, two police officers take cover in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were instructed by the state government to guard the office of Riodos, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these police officers were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officials about whom the governor himself said they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto under the control of drug gangs.
In the next issue of "Riodos" counted on three main topics.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had an exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the prosecutor's office.
It was not officially announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was the favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which dominated all levels of power for almost the entire last century.
Several PRI governors have recently been indicted on high-profile corruption charges.
Villareal asked reporters to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when Guzman’s son El Chapo escaped a military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have looked for Valdez’s column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
“We would have known what had happened before,” says Villareal, 46, for his lean physique, nicknamed “El Flaco.”
"Today, all channels of communication with our sources have been severed."
Valdez’s office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killing of journalists because employees have become what they never thought they would become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took some posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor’s office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacan in the west of the country three days after Valdez was killed.
Found the burned body, and the authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Throughout the country, journalists began to speak out, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorquez was in Washington, D.C., seeking international support for the Valdez case.
In a meeting with Governor Sinaloa the day after Valdez’s murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their murders for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to give her any more assignments to cover the government’s activities, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdés has said many times that journalists in Mexico are “surrounded” by organized crime, its complicity in government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, “Drug Journalism,” he wrote that reporters are killed not just by drug gangs; they do so on the orders of politicians and security services colluding with organized crime.
The Articulo 19 Press Protection Committee estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,” Ramirez says.
Of course, killing scares people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I'm here because of my articles."
A computer keyboard and headphones were lying next to her severed head.
Some publications chose to close as El Norte newspaper in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslava Brich was killed in March.
Others continue to hold on as "El Manyana" from Nuevo Laredo after the murder of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, the Diario de Ciudad Juarez made a public appeal to drug cartels through an editorial on the front page entitled "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have left their home states or even the country.
It's a painful decision.
It is difficult to find work in exile, and they are still looking for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work daily balance between risky decisions.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is afraid to write about the drug trade.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready for publication, the publishers of Riodos were sitting on the sidewalk next to the office and drinking beer, when suddenly their phones simultaneously rang.
A series of skirmishes between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Masatlan left behind, according to confirmed data, 19 corpses.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from cartels discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted news via their mobile phone on the Riodos website.
The next day, the first page had to be redesigned.
There were sirens nearby, another shooting in the vicinity.
Bochorkes looked at whether the police officers guarding them were ready for defense.
If they were scared, they didn’t show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was exposed to the whole of Sinaloa, the Riodos employees continued his work.
"How can you think of closing down," said Bohorkes, "if the same day Javier was killed, the intern asked me to send her outside to do a reportage?"
Dinosaurs Use Camouflage to Avoid Enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit terrifying.
The researchers said that the first found remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhino discovered by a Canadian miner, preserved so well that experts called it “Mona Lisa among dinosaurs”.
It is so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown — and to say that he had, in some ways, a “dark past.”
The report, published in the journal Modern Biology, described it as "the best preserved of the Tireophores ever found and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition stunned researchers, who call him “really remarkable.”
This herbivorous tireophore is the best preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Suncore Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed different from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was underway to detect an animal inside an earth block weighing 2,500 feet (1,100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
“It’s only worth squinting a little bit, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is being demonstrated.
“It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs — the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
Studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite the fact that it was covered with shell and resembled a walking tank, was apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This heavily shelled dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals of our day.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with the environment and avoid meeting enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaur family, was widely reported in print in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum laboratory technician Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours behind its painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international group of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and shell plates on his body.
They found a protective coloration, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its lower side.
Although protective coloration is common, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of the currently living animals with protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration - for example, deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and are more affordable prey, which indicates that the nodosaur had to seriously fight for survival.
“A serious predatory threat to a massive, heavily shelled dinosaur shows just how dangerous the Cretaceous dinosaurs were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in dinosaur scales also suggests that its skin should have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried into the sea, where it sank and laid its back down to the bottom of the ocean.
In those days, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans likely spread much further inland than they are now.
“This nodosaur is truly remarkable for being completely covered in preserved scaly skin, and at the same time fully preserved in three dimensions, preserving the animal’s original shape,” Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did back in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use the imagination to recreate it, you just have to squint a little, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous period is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of these, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the tireophore could have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
These include the acrocantosaurus, a monster 38 feet (11.5 meters) long, weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest discoveries are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was taken to sea after death and mummified in silt.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to museum staff, it is the best preserved tireophore in the world, along with skin and shell, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the hip bones.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous tireophore set a heavy foot on what is now Canada, until a spilled river carried it into the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell with precision to the smallest details.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is “rare as winning the lottery.”
The longer I look at him, the more amazing he seems.
Fossilized skin remains still cover the bumpy shell plates that dot the animal's skull.
His right front leg is stretched out along the side, five fingers on it are turned up.
I can count the scales on his sole."
