How did one activist find out the answer to the question “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York as part of a tourist trip, a St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, browsing the Facebook feed on her phone.
She ran into someone from high school.
It read: “Police have just killed an eighteen-year-old child and he is still lying in the middle of the street.”
Paying attention to the fact that no one else from her tape posted this information, puzzled, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
There were a lot of user reposts in her tape with the nickname ?TheePharoah.
A rapper from Greater St. Louis tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black eighteen-year-old murdered by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown’s lifeless body spread out in the middle of the street, where it would be four hours away.
“It’s wild,” Ferrel thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put her phone down, and later that evening returned to tweets that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of a signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a poster saying, "Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live broadcast as a police officer stands in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, pulled up the trigger of a rifle and yelled, “I’m going to kill you all... animals!”
“It’s a non-standard situation,” Ferrel said at the time.
“It’s not a murder like the ones we’re used to and can call typical.
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and crying.”
She took a ticket for the return flight and flew home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she took her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrel and Ferguson in the next almost three years was the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
This is a story about survival and protest, about love and loss, strength and resilience in terms of people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrel was driving to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and a wreath for color, they recalled a conversation that had been conducted countless times before this morning, "about the experiences of blacks and their situation."
She recalls saying, “Remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We're going to Ferguson right now because a policeman killed an eighteen-year-old boy and it was wrong."
"I couldn't help but take her," Ferrell later said.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what has happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it and be brought up on it.
It must not only be well-versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their positions and what we must do to become free to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would do her a disservice if I shielded her from it."
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florissant Road, a site across the street from the police station that had become something of a tent camp, while activists waited for reports of the final inculcation of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrel and her daughter joined a local entrepreneur who was preparing lunch packages.
They collected packages and helped distribute them to protesters.
Little by little, Ferrel took the form of a new type of activism.
“My activism completely changed after August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Nursing Students, a national minority, and dealt with food justice and health inequalities among black communities.
“I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrel met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her main cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?”
This skepticism was inspired by numerous people, often white, who came to the community in order to benefit from its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don’t get the spotlight and wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row issues.
His involvement sparked sympathy for the project from Ferrell and six other locals with whom the Whose Streets project team had been in touch for years after Brown's murder.
