Startups that will help your company not to become another “Uber”
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among the employees of her startup in the field of e-commerce, but the polls did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs San Francisco-based 75-person company Madison Reed, an e-commerce company in the hair care industry.
So she turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of startups in the field of work with staff, which help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to make express surveys, reach out to certain teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact the directorate directly.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has gained a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel in three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies gradually realize that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another “Uber”, which was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post in which he described an aggressive environment in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to estimates of the online portal “Let’s talk about payment”, dedicated to financial technologies, the industry of global governance, regulation and compliance by 2020 can cost more than 118.7 billion dollars.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber’s declining reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom-made opinion polls to staff, collect confidential real-time responses, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages, which allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that a company mistreats employees or behaves unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are up-to-date with the rules and procedures and to offer an easy way to reach out to the company’s head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a phone number or head office email, file a formal complaint, and hope to be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of the legal department at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that used to be hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay — can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who leads the network’s risk management group Ruby Tuesday.
“And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take employee ethics, values, and engagement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Affair.
But it wasn’t until “social media went viral” that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty underwear from spreading virally online.
“Before we started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture capitalists, who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company’s total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In markets with fierce competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just a necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are being accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work at a company, feel heard, and that the work they do produces results, they are more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when businesses in their portfolio do well; businesses do well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on the involvement of employees.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if change doesn’t come quickly enough, or doesn’t come at all, frustration can develop and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be willing to have 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, employees will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
If you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day someone reports a problem with Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it to more effectively retain employees in an industry known for high staff turnover.
“If you’re not trying to create a culture of transparency, you’re going to lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose companies.
