Create a comic book novel: One lock in English history
In the recent past, the tiny castle of Scottie was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the valley of the river Bull in Kent, he watched the turbulent history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a spear of hair and a penchant for historical documents, for a comic novel.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
Castle in England spans from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells the story of families who lived in Scotty; each story is illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This isn’t Rhodes’ first book based on archival data: In 2014, he wrote Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of British Library documents that unexpectedly touched him to his core.
“I could have been touched simply by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for Jacobites,” he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those days for lighting lit the fire.
And after 300 years, in the future, it seems to you that you are there too.
Oh, how I love the archives!
For a man so obsessed with old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the English Arts Council and living in the castle for four months ("Honestly, I'm a little bit queer there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent all day studying the "new" Victorian castle, went through the archives and considered numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, hyena heads on walls or bottles, centuries lying in a ditch.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners, and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotty Castle is not much studied because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006 when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were just beginning to sort out the archive, which he describes as "what aristocrats have been dumping in the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think that land disputes are boring,” Rhodes says, “but this is what two families fought for.
It happens, guys!”
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider explorations in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is evidence of a riot that occurred at the castle in 1380, in a book called 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,'" Rhodes says.
“The peasant revolt started in these places, and I thought that the revolt was the right beginning.
Maybe they were connected?”
Other stories are strongly connected with the history of the castle - for example, "Priest", which tells about a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler," about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoning the coffin (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are Rhodes's favorite family of all who inhabited Scottie: "Gentlemen seem to have been perfect scammers, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrel men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I imagine them as a company of cute guys who know how to care for the heirs of big fortunes.
After finishing work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamyanmyaki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again overgrown with forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he says.
“I felt like, ‘Damn, I have to go back to real life again.’
