Trump's big move?
To pretend to be Mita Romney seems very reasonable.
In the Trump era, a common place was the fact that the political disputes that polarized the American electorate broke up some families at the micro level.
Between Thanksgiving and Christmas, American newspapers were full of columns about how to deal with the terrible relatives voting for Trump.
Looks like we're all so tense we're gonna burst.
There is less talk about Trump’s ability to connect families.
I’m writing about it because my cousin, a left-wing poet from Chicago who has long been on knives with Republicans in her family, came to see me in New York this week.
She reminded me that uniting against a common enemy can have a strong effect.
Under Trump in the White House, everyone she knows, including her Republican brother, with whom she’s been arguing about politics for decades, suddenly and strangely ended up on the same side.
Over dinner it is undoubtedly good; but I cannot help but think that in a broader context it can be quite dangerous.
Trump has breathed strength into the left flank, but the deforming effect of his rule can move us all to the right.
When we talk about Trump and “normalization,” we mean the unlikely possibility that one day we will no longer be struck by his antics.
There is, however, an even more dubious scenario in which Trump “normalizes” the most right-wing Republicans, who, against the background of his standards, will suddenly seem a model of common sense.
I caught myself missing out on Mitt Romney’s old-fashioned madness today — with a dog on the roof of the car and a 14 percent income tax (but we at least knew what his tax return looked like) — compared to Trump, both seem like very little evil.
When Trump leaves, the next Republican candidate will just have to be in his mind to be seen as a huge step forward.
