White House Requisition Costs Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One" when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 event at the White House that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials inspected technology products from all fifty states.
A Connecticut-made helicopter was on display next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi forklift.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter control, the White House Military Administration ordered the helicopter's presence in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
“I just wanted you to make sure you’re aware because this is an unusual widely publicized event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his boss, the Marine Corps’ first deputy chief of aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be needed for the return flight in accordance with restrictions on working hours.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel stayed close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event contradicted this ruling.
“Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of Hatch’s law and we were told it wasn’t,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go,” replied the deputy chief.
“Made in America” was announced by the White House as an official event, and Hatch’s law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote health care reform, which was then in the works in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft, known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to request them only in the interests of photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of debate in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is littered with messages complaining about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled with the ‘Made in America’ show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House spokeswoman Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House to within an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 had 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the event "Made in America" was credited to the crew for the necessary training flights for the month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of "non-presidential support tasks."
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Defense Department’s 2017 fiscal year hourly rates, the Defense Department’s reimbursement rate for VH-3Ds is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit's records state that the flight time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its base airfield at Quantico Marine Corps Air Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on the approximate reimbursement rate is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, maintenance and many other non-recoverable costs that are included in the annual appropriations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of using the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to showcase things made in America this week,” Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
So, of course, it is appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump had interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he certainly sat at the driver’s seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said.
