Electricity is cheaper for both residents and producers of Buryatia
The decades-long efforts of the Soviet and post-Soviet authorities of the Republic of Buryatia (Eastern Siberia) to establish fair tariffs for electricity consumers are beginning to bear fruit.
Since September 1, the cost of electricity in low voltage for industrial recipients has been reduced by 25%.
The Federal Antimonopoly Service of the country in accordance with the Decree of the Government of the Russian Federation "On Amendments to the Rules of the Wholesale Electricity and Power Market and the Consolidated Forecast Balance of Electricity Production and Supply (Capacity) within the Unified Energy System of Russia for the Subjects of the Russian Federation" (as of July 17, 2017 No. 842) established indicative prices for electricity and capacity for industrial consumers of the Republic of Buryatia.
As a result, the cost of electricity for Buryat producers is reduced by a quarter, which will greatly facilitate the lives of small and medium-sized enterprises and individual entrepreneurs.
For many decades, the leaders of the republic have been beating the thresholds of Moscow offices in vain attempts to equate the region in tariffs with the neighboring Irkutsk region with a cascade of hydroelectric power stations on Angara, flowing from Lake Baikal, the main catchment area for which is Buryatia.
And only this year began the movement.
In March, electricity tariffs for the population of the republic were reduced from 4.24 rubles/kWh to 3.93 rubles/kWh, or 7.3%.
With the inclusion of Buryatia by the decision of the federal government in the list of territories of wholesale market price zones, for which the features of the wholesale and retail markets are established, the turn of industrial consumers has come.
According to analysts, this is only the beginning, since the population of the Irkutsk region pays for a kilowatt hour of 1.01 rubles.
But no one dares to name at least the approximate date of new tariff changes downwards for Buryatia.
