National Union of unskilled, municipal and boiler workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment at the factory McVitie's in Glasgow
The union is seeking assurances from McVitie's biscuit maker's managers over its long-term production commitment at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company went silent on the issue of future investment in the Tolkros facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, cookies Hobnobs and Rich Tea, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, said it had invested more than 5 million pounds in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in case of any changes in the work of the object, employees and representatives of the trade union “will learn about them first.”
In a letter to the head of the facility owned by the company, the Scottish branch of GMB demanded from McVitie's reaction to the concern that funding would not be used to modernize production lines.
Drew Duffy, senior organizer, said: “Members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot obtain clarity from the CEO of the business needs and investment plan facility regarding the future of Tolcross.
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in the territory of Greater Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
So, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and amid Brexit, rising living wage and chronic production decline, Glasgow’s East End desperately needs the prosperity of manufacturing at McVitie’s factory.
According to Pladis, “The head of the Tolkros facility only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our constant cooperation with employees and representatives of the union.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tolcross, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to our employees about the fact that like all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions - and this applies to all our facilities and activities - in order to remain competitive.
“In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tolkros facility, especially in production lines and improving functional performance.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in case of any changes in the work at this facility, employees and representatives of the trade union will be the first to know about it.”
Putin said that the authorities will not give instructions to Rosneft and Gazprom
Vladimir Putin said that the question of gas supplies to the Eastern Petrochemical Company (VNKhK) should be connected to the Kremlin and the Cabinet of Ministers, but no one will give instructions to Gazprom, as well as Rosneft.
Thus, Russian President Vladimir Putin responded to Igor Sechin’s request to help resolve the contradictions that have arisen.
The head of state drew attention to the fact that relations between Rosneft and Gazprom should be resolved solely on the basis of market principles.
Earlier, the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin at a meeting on the implementation of major investment projects in the Far Eastern Federal District said that the lack of agreement with Gazprom on gas for VNKhK jeopardizes the implementation of the project.
Sechin noted that the dialogue with Gazprom on this issue continues.
"Gazprom offers to find gas resources from the perimeter of Rosneft, but we do not have such resources," Sechin added.
Recall that Rosneft asked to allow it to use gas from the Kirinskoye field of Gazprom, located on the shelf of Sakhalin, for the Eastern Petrochemical Company.
In June, Gazprom said that negotiations on this issue are continuing, and “there are no sharp corners there.”
Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar’s move three years ago?
The member of “La Liga” may regret his interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not stop chasing Neymar after the club offered 189 million pounds for his ransom, but did they warn Barcelona about the world record raid that took place three years ago?
The sensational offer enlivened the summer transfer window when Ligue 1 club was ready to break the world record for the cost of the transfer, more than twice the previous mark associated with the return of Paul Pogba to Manchester United last season for 89 million pounds.
When the transition is complete, Neymar will become the most expensive player in the world, as well as the highest paid professional athlete in the world, as PSG offers him a salary of more than 500,000 pounds per week net.
It is known that Barcelona are furious with how the proposal was made and how Neymar broke the contract, despite the fact that, according to a source close to the leadership of the Catalan club, the club has always done everything possible for the player since his transition from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world warned of such a possibility three years ago by the PSG president?
When Manchester City expressed interest in hiring Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi issued a stern warning to any club that would like to lure one of PSG's best players.
“I’m not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we will come against them, we will make offers to their players,” Al-Khelaifi said.
“We respect all the clubs.
But if they try to recruit one of our players, they will have consequences.”
Apparently, Barcelona crossed this line when the Spanish club earlier this summer expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti.
PSG have made it clear that they will not let go of the Italian player on any terms, and now probably Barcelona feels the consequences of their offer in the form of the loss of one of their most valuable players, Neymar.
